Step 2 Spatial data in the sp package

Making a point dataset

#sp Points
x<-c(8,8,7)
y<-c(2,3,4)
xy<-data.frame(x,y)
pointCoords<-SpatialPoints(xy)
uid<-c("1","2","3")
species<-c("Dinornis robustus","Anomalopteryx didiformis","Dinornis robustus")
data<-data.frame(uid,species)
pointData<-SpatialPointsDataFrame(pointCoords,data)

Step 3 Spatial data using the sf package

Point

#Point
point1<-st_point(c(8,2))
point2<-st_point(c(8,3))
point3<-st_point(c(7,4))
pointCollection<-st_sfc(point1,point2,point3)
uid<-c("1","2","3")
species<-c("Dinornis robustus","Anomalopteryx didiformis","Dinornis robustus")
data<-data.frame(uid,species)
pointData<-st_sf(data,pointCollection)

Linestring

#Linestring
lineMatrix1<-rbind(c(8, 2), c(8, 3), c(7, 4))
lineMatrix2<-rbind(c(13, 6), c(11, 8), c(9, 8))
lineString1<-st_linestring(lineMatrix1)
lineString2<-st_linestring(lineMatrix2)
lineCollection<-st_sfc(lineString1,lineString2)
transectNum<-c("transect1","transect2")
faunaPresent<-c(TRUE,FALSE)
data<-data.frame(transectNum,faunaPresent)
lineData<-st_sf(data,lineCollection)

Polygon

#Polygon
polygonList = list(rbind(c(8, 2, 1), c(8, 3, 3), c(7, 4, 2), c(9, 8, 2), c(11, 8, 3),c(13, 6, 4), c(8, 2, 1)))
polygonObject<-st_polygon(polygonList)
polygonCollection<-st_sfc(polygonObject)
featureNum<-c(8675309)
featureType<-c("Residential")
data<-data.frame(featureNum,featureType)
polygonData<-st_sf(data,polygonCollection)

An sf class object

Step 4 Coercion and conversion

#Coercing from xy table
x<-c(8,8,7)
y<-c(2,3,4)
data<-c("yes","yes","no")
xy<-data.frame(x,y,data)
pointData<-st_as_sf(xy,coords=c("x","y"))

#Coercing from sp object
x<-c(8,8,7)
y<-c(2,3,4)
xy<-data.frame(x,y)
pointCoords<-SpatialPoints(xy)
uid<-c("1","2","3")
species<-c("Dinornis robustus","Anomalopteryx didiformis","Dinornis robustus")
data<-data.frame(uid,species)
pointData<-SpatialPointsDataFrame(pointCoords,data)

sfPointData<-st_as_sf(pointData)

Step 8 Plotting data

#Plotting everything
plot(scalds)

#Plotting this way will remove geometry
plot(scalds$width)

#Plotting this way will keep geometry intact
plot(scalds['width'])

#plot geometry
plot(st_geometry(catchment),axes=T)
plot(st_geometry(streams),col="navy blue",add=T)
plot(st_geometry(scalds),pch=16,cex=0.1,add=T)
bigScalds<-subset(scalds,length>500)
plot(st_geometry(bigScalds),cex=0.2,col="red",add=T)

Step X Projecting data

#Import map of South Africa, Lesotho, and Eswatini
southernAfrica<-st_read('south_africa_border.shp')
## Reading layer `south_africa_border' from data source 
##   `C:\Users\bdav_\Dropbox\Teaching\Spatial R Short Course\Lectures\Lecture1\south_africa_border.shp' 
##   using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 3 features and 94 fields
## Geometry type: POLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: 16.46998 ymin: -34.82195 xmax: 32.89308 ymax: -22.12645
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
#Reproject to Albers Equal Area Conic
southernAfricaReproject<-st_transform(southernAfrica,"+proj=aea +lat_1=20 +lat_2=-23 +lat_0=0 +lon_0=25 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +units=m +no_defs")

#Plot them both with axes
plot(st_geometry(southernAfrica),axes=TRUE,main="EQUIRECTANGULAR")

plot(st_geometry(southernAfricaReproject),axes=TRUE,main="ALBERS EQUAL AREA CONIC")

#Step X Exporting data

#Generate large point data set near Johannesburg
x<-rnorm(1000,28,1)
y<-rnorm(1000,-26,1)
data<-rep("This is a point.",1000)
xy<-data.frame(x,y,data)
pointData<-st_as_sf(xy,coords=c("x","y"))

#Add CRS (WGS84)
st_crs(pointData) <- 4326

#Plot the data on a map of southern Africa
plot(st_geometry(southernAfrica))

#Export the data
plot(st_geometry(pointData),add=T)

st_write(pointData,"bunchofpoints.shp",driver="ESRI shapefile")
## Writing layer `bunchofpoints' to data source 
##   `bunchofpoints.shp' using driver `ESRI shapefile'
## Writing 1000 features with 1 fields and geometry type Point.
